      <file>projects/ai-spaarke-action-engine-r1/coordination-assessment-with-insights-engine.md</file>
    </files>
    <patterns>
      <pattern name="Job Contract pattern" location=".claude/patterns/api/background-workers.md">Existing `IJobHandler&lt;T&gt;` + `ServiceBusJobProcessor` consumption pattern; scheduler output MUST be SB-compatible or route through SB.</pattern>
      <pattern name="Feature-module DI" location=".claude/patterns/api/service-registration.md">`AddActionEngineModule()` extension; ≤15 non-framework registrations per ADR-010.</pattern>
      <pattern name="Insights Engine Track B Hybrid D" location="docs/architecture/AI-ARCHITECTURE.md">Same pattern shape; document why it transfers to Action Engine or why it doesn't.</pattern>
    </patterns>
  </knowledge>

  <steps>
    <step order="0">Context check: confirm working tree clean, branch is `work/ai-spaarke-action-engine-r1`, baseline build passes. (task-execute Step 0)</step>
    <step order="1">Read all files in `&lt;knowledge&gt;&lt;files&gt;` — especially spec.md §15 (open questions), design.md §6 (Runtime and Hosting), and `bff-extensions.md` (binding governance).</step>
    <step order="2">Build comparison matrix for scheduler options (Logic Apps timer / Service Bus scheduled message / Functions timer / Container Apps Jobs). Columns: cost at expected volume (assume 100–1000 scheduled Actions/day per tenant); operational complexity (deployment, monitoring, alerting); integration cost with existing `ServiceBusJobProcessor`; max cron resolution; multi-tenant isolation; observability via App Insights; failure-mode handling. Save to `notes/spikes/scheduler-comparison.md`.</step>
    <step order="3">Recommend a scheduler choice with explicit rationale. If recommendation is anything other than the default (Service Bus scheduled message, which integrates seamlessly with `ServiceBusJobProcessor`), justify the deviation against ADR-001 + ADR-004 + the bff-extensions.md pre-merge checklist.</step>
    <step order="4">Build Action Engine module skeleton in a scratch branch or local-only path: create `Services/Ai/ActionEngine/` folder with placeholder `ActionOrchestrationService.cs` (just the class shell + DI registration), `PublicContracts/IActionEngineFacade.cs` (interface only), `Models/ActionDefinition.cs` (data class), and `AddActionEngineModule()` extension. Add Azure AI Search client NuGet reference (`Azure.Search.Documents`). Add `Microsoft.SemanticKernel` references ONLY if not already transitively present (check with `dotnet list package --include-transitive | grep SemanticKernel`).</step>
    <step order="5">Measure publish-size delta: run `dotnet publish src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/ --configuration Release --runtime linux-x64 --self-contained false` BEFORE and AFTER the skeleton additions. Capture compressed delta (zip the publish output, compare). Record measurements in `notes/spikes/publish-size-measurement.md`. Verify delta ≤ 5 MB compressed. If delta exceeds budget, identify which package is the bloat source and propose mitigations (e.g., use existing AI Search client if already loaded; consume Semantic Kernel only via existing surface).</step>
    <step order="6">**Hybrid D runtime confirmation**: enumerate the multi-step probabilistic Action scenarios in MVP scope (from spec.md and the three starter Templates in design.md). For each, validate whether `SprkChatAgent` + `UseFunctionInvocation` handles: multi-step tool-call chains, conditional branching, parameter elicitation, error recovery. Document scenario-by-scenario in `notes/spikes/hybrid-d-validation.md`. If any scenario requires Microsoft Agent Framework, scope it OUT of MVP (defer to R2) — do not introduce a new runtime in MVP.</step>
    <step order="7">**Revert spike artifacts**: roll back the module skeleton from step 4 (we don't want spike code in main). Task 014 will properly create the production skeleton with the chosen scheduler integration baked in. Confirm `git status` is clean except for the new files under `projects/ai-spaarke-action-engine-r1/notes/`.</step>
    <step order="8">Write the runtime ADR draft at `projects/ai-spaarke-action-engine-r1/notes/decisions/runtime-topology-ADR-draft.md` covering: scheduler choice + rationale, publish-size measurement + headroom, Hybrid D confirmation + MVP scope confirmation. Use ADR-001-style format (Status / Context / Decision / Consequences). This becomes the basis for the formal ADR added to `docs/adr/` during Phase 6.</step>
    <step order="9">Update `plan.md` Phase 4 deliverables to reference the confirmed scheduler choice. Update Risk Register: mark R1 (publish-size) and R2 (scheduler choice) status as resolved (or escalated if measurements failed budget).</step>
    <step order="9.5">Run quality gates: `code-review` on `notes/decisions/runtime-topology-ADR-draft.md` (substantive review, not just lint); `adr-check` is N/A here (no code) but verify the draft cites ADRs explicitly.</step>
    <step order="10">Update `tasks/TASK-INDEX.md`: mark task 001 status ✅, record scheduler choice in the "Decisions" appendix. Update `current-task.md`: task 001 complete; next action: "begin Phase 1 (Group A: tasks 010, 011, 012, 013 parallel)".</step>
    <step order="11">Document any deviations from this plan in `projects/ai-spaarke-action-engine-r1/notes/handoffs/` and add a brief commit message recap.</step>
  </steps>

